[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] In computer programming, **event-driven programming** is a programming paradigm in which the flow of the program is determined by external events.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] User interface (UI) events from keyboards and mice, touchpads and touchscreens, and external sensor inputs are common cases.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] Events may also be programmatically generated, such as from messages from other programs, notifications from other threads, or other network events.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programming is the dominant paradigm used in graphical user interface (GUI) applications and network servers.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] In an event-driven application, there is generally an event loop that listens for events and then triggers a callback function when one of those events is detected.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programs can be written in any programming language, although the task is easier in languages that provide high-level abstractions.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] Although they do not exactly fit the event-driven model, interrupt handling and exception handling have many similarities.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] It is important to differentiate between event-driven and message-driven (aka queue-driven) paradigms: event-driven services (e.g.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] AWS SNS) are decoupled from their consumers, whereas message/queue-driven services (e.g.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] AWS SQS) are coupled with their consumers.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] Because the event loop that retrieves and dispatches events is common amongst applications, many programming frameworks provide an implementation of an event loop, and the application developer only needs to write the event handlers.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] The actual logic is contained in event handler routines.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] These routines handle the events to which the main program will respond.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] For example, a single mouse-click on a "Save" command button in a GUI program might trigger a routine to save data to a database.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] An "Exit" button might trigger a routine to exit the program.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] The event loop receives events from all such command buttons and other GUI elements, dispatching the appropriate event handler routine for each button.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] Event handler routines need to be bound to specific events, so the event loop can dispatch the correct routine in response to the event.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] Many IDEs simplify this process by providing the programmer with an event handling template for each specific event (such as a button click), allowing the programmer to focus on writing the event-handling code.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] In a sequential program, keeping track of execution order and history is normally trivial.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] But in an event-driven program, event handlers execute non-sequentially in response to external events.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] Special attention and planning is required to correctly structure the event handlers to work when called in any order.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] Most existing GUI architectures use event-driven programming.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] The Java AWT framework processes all UI changes on a single thread, called the Event dispatching thread.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] Similarly, all UI updates in the Java framework JavaFX occur on the JavaFX Application Thread.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/event-driven-programming] Most network servers and frameworks such as Node.js are also event-driven.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/function-as-a-service] Function as a Service is a subset of the serverless computing ecosystem.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/function-as-a-service] The "Grain of Sand Anti-pattern" refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/function-as-a-service] "Lambda Pinball" is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure Functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/function-as-a-service] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/function-as-a-service] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/function-as-a-service] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/function-as-a-service] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/function-as-a-service] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/function-as-a-service] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/function-as-a-service] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/function-as-a-service] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/function-as-a-service] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/function-as-a-service] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/function-as-a-service] Function as a service workloads may encounter migration obstacles due to service lock-in from tight vendor integrations.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/function-as-a-service] Hexagonal architecture can facilitate workload portability.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/google-cloud-platform] Google Cloud provides infrastructure as a service, platform as a service, and serverless computing environments.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/google-cloud-platform] In April 2008, Google announced App Engine, a platform for developing and hosting web applications in Google-managed data centers, which was the first cloud computing service from the company.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/google-cloud-platform] The service became generally available in November 2011.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/google-cloud-platform] Since the announcement of App Engine, Google added multiple cloud services to the platform.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/google-cloud-platform] Google lists over 100 products under the Google Cloud brand.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/google-cloud-platform] Some of the key services are listed below.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/google-cloud-platform] A region is a specific geographical location where users can deploy cloud resources.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/google-cloud-platform] Each region is an independent geographic area that consists of zones.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/google-cloud-platform] A zone is a deployment area for Google Cloud Platform resources within a region.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/google-cloud-platform] Zones should be considered a single failure domain within a region.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/google-cloud-platform] As of Q1 2024, Google Cloud Platform is available in 40 regions and 121 zones.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/google-cloud-platform] For those familiar with other notable cloud service providers, a comparison of similar services may be helpful in understanding Google Cloud Platform's offerings.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/google-cloud-platform] Customers announced in 2023 include Kingfisher plc, the Government of Kuwait, Deutsche Börse Group, Unity Technologies, Uber, FanCode, Daimler, and Wix.com.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] The term was introduced by American mathematician Benjamin Peirce in 1870 in the context of elements of algebras that remain invariant when raised to a positive integer power, and literally means "(the quality of having) the same power", from *idem* + *potence* (same + power).
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] If the set E has n elements, we can partition it into k chosen fixed points and $n-k$ non-fixed points under f , and then $k^{n-k}$ is the number of different idempotent functions.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] is the total number of possible idempotent functions on the set.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] Neither idempotence nor non-idempotence is preserved under function composition.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] As an example for the former, $f(x)=x$ mod 3 and $g(x)=\max(x,5)$ are both idempotent, but $f\circ g$ is not, although $g\circ f$ happens to be.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] As an example for the latter, the negation function $\neg$ on the Boolean domain is not idempotent, but $\neg \circ \neg$ is.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] Similarly, unary negation $-(\cdot )$ of real numbers is not idempotent, but $-(\cdot )\circ -(\cdot )$ is.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] In both cases, the composition is simply the identity function, which is idempotent.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] A morphism $f:x\to x$ in a category is called *idempotent* if $f\circ f=f$ .
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] An idempotent is said to *split* if it can be written as $f=h\circ g$ for some $g:x\to y,\,h:y\to x$ with $g\circ h=\operatorname {id}$ .
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] A category is said to be idempotent complete if every idempotent splits.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] For example, ${\mathsf {Set}}$ is idempotent complete.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] This is a very useful property in many situations, as it means that an operation can be repeated or retried as often as necessary without causing unintended effects.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] With non-idempotent operations, the algorithm may have to keep track of whether the operation was already performed or not.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] A function looking up a customer's name and address in a database is typically idempotent, since this will not cause the database to change.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] Similarly, a request for changing a customer's address to XYZ is typically idempotent, because the final address will be the same no matter how many times the request is submitted.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] However, a customer request for placing an order is typically not idempotent since multiple requests will lead to multiple orders being placed.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] A request for canceling a particular order is idempotent because no matter how many requests are made the order remains canceled.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] A sequence of idempotent subroutines where at least one subroutine is different from the others, however, is not necessarily idempotent if a later subroutine in the sequence changes a value that an earlier subroutine depends on—*idempotence is not closed under sequential composition*.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] For example, suppose the initial value of a variable is 3 and there is a subroutine sequence that reads the variable, then changes it to 5, and then reads it again.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] Each step in the sequence is idempotent: both steps reading the variable have no side effects and the step changing the variable to 5 will always have the same effect no matter how many times it is executed.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] Nonetheless, executing the entire sequence once produces the output (3, 5), but executing it a second time produces the output (5, 5), so the sequence is not idempotent.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] In the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), idempotence and safety are the major attributes that separate HTTP methods.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] Of the major HTTP methods, GET, PUT, and DELETE should be implemented in an idempotent manner according to the standard, but POST doesn't need to be.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] GET retrieves the state of a resource; PUT updates the state of a resource; and DELETE deletes a resource.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] As in the example above, reading data usually has no side effects, so it is idempotent (in fact *nullipotent*).
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] Updating and deleting a given data are each usually idempotent as long as the request uniquely identifies the resource and only that resource again in the future.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] PUT and DELETE with unique identifiers reduce to the simple case of assignment to a variable of either a value or the null-value, respectively, and are idempotent for the same reason; the end result is always the same as the result of the initial execution, even if the response differs.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] Violation of the unique identification requirement in storage or deletion typically causes violation of idempotence.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] Similarly, PUT and DELETE requests with nonspecific criteria may result in different outcomes depending on the state of the system – for example, a request to delete the most recent record.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] In each case, subsequent executions will further modify the state of the system, so they are not idempotent.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] In event stream processing, idempotence refers to the ability of a system to produce the same outcome, even if the same file, event or message is received more than once.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] In a load–store architecture, instructions that might possibly cause a page fault are idempotent.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] So if a page fault occurs, the operating system can load the page from disk and then simply re-execute the faulted instruction.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] In a processor where such instructions are not idempotent, dealing with page faults is much more complex.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] When reformatting output, pretty-printing is expected to be idempotent.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] In other words, if the output is already "pretty", there should be nothing to do for the pretty-printer.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] In service-oriented architecture (SOA), a multiple-step orchestration process composed entirely of idempotent steps can be replayed without side-effects if any part of that process fails.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] Many operations that are idempotent often have ways to "resume" a process if it is interrupted – ways that finish much faster than starting all over from the beginning.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] For example, resuming a file transfer, synchronizing files, creating a software build, installing an application and all of its dependencies with a package manager, etc.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] Applied examples that many people could encounter in their day-to-day lives include elevator call buttons and crosswalk buttons.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] The initial activation of the button moves the system into a requesting state, until the request is satisfied.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] Subsequent activations of the button between the initial activation and the request being satisfied have no effect, unless the system is designed to adjust the time for satisfying the request based on the number of activations.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] Similarly, the elevator "close" button may be pressed many times to the same effect as once, since the doors close on a fixed schedule – unless the "open" button is pressed.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/idempotence] The "open" button is not idempotent, because each press adds further delay.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:gcp-cloud-functions/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
